âThe goal of WAR is to provide a holistic metric of player value that allows for comparisons across team, league, year, and era and a framework for player evaluation.â

The work in this article moves WAR closer to its goal of providing fair comparisons of players who have played in vastly different eras. This matters when we evaluate a playerâs career in historical context. The Hall of Fame (HOF) players of the old past are beneficiaries of a biased performance metrics. Comparisons based upon âvs your peersâ statistics are therefore slanted in favor of old time playersâspecifically those who performed in the segregated NL/AL. Now this is no more. The Babe Ruth anomaly

Babe Ruth revolutionized baseball by prioritizing home run hitting as the MLB livened the baseball. As stated here, the single season home run record before Babe Ruth was 27 by Ned Williamson in 1884. Babe Ruth broke this record in 1919 when he hit 29 home runs. He subsequently destroyed his own record in the following 1920 season when he hit 54 home runs. The runner up in 1920 finished the season with only 15 home runs. This level of dominance has never been seen before and has never been seen sense, and it poses a problem for era-adjustment techniques.

Babe Ruthâs dominance is in part due to his talent, but is also in part to him exercising a superior batting strategy that had not existed before. Therefore, Ruthâs âvs his peersâ stats are slightly distorted, and his era-adjusted stats will also be distorted as a result. Ruthâs projected stats into the 2021 context will reflect the combination of his talent and his competitive advantage, a competitive advantage that would not exist in todayâs context. Our method will therefore overestimate Ruthâs era-adjusted home run hitting and his era-adjusted WAR since our method does not yet disentangle talent and competitivie circumstance. The problem of the Babe Ruth anomaly confounds all era-adjustment techniques. We imagine that Ruthâs era-adjusted OBP is also overestimated by our method. The Babe Ruth anomaly challenges all other era-adjustment techniques, and is especially challenging for anyone making interpretations based solely on raw or league adjusted â+â stats.

The Tony Gwynn anomaly

Tony Gwynn has the highest era-adjusted batting average by a mile (See part I). He was a truly amazing hitter who stood very far from his peers. However, like Babe Ruth, a portion of his dominance is due to circumstance. Gywnn was one of the early pioneers of using film to study his strengths and weaknesses as well as the strengths and weaknesses of the pitchers that he faced. Nowadays film study is a basic training method available to everyone in the MLB and it is unusual and worth mentioning when great players do not use it. Therefore, like Ruth, Gwynnâs batting average stats are slightly distorted, and his era-adjusted stats will also be distorted as a result. Gwynnâs projected stats into the 2021 context will reflect the combination of his talent and his competitive advantage, a competitive advantage that would not exist in todayâs context. Our method will therefore overestimate Gwynnâs era-adjusted batting average and his era-adjusted WAR as a result.

Letâs visit ZiPS Projections before we conclude this work. Dan Szymborski closes a recent article with a discussion on outlandish Juan Soto projections to which he says

âIâll admit it: I just wanted to see Soto break ZiPS. And I think he might have. Last spring, I spent some time talking with Jayson Stark about whether Soto was the next Ted Williams. Here are the outlandish percentile Soto projections that Szymborski references:

Szymborski refers to Soto as breaking ZiPS. In other words, the projection system is unreliable for Soto. We do not think that players break projection systems. Rather, projection systems are themselves broken if they produce nonsensical forecasts for players. We do not know the inner mechanics of the ZiPS Projection System. If it borrows information from great players of the past to inform predictions about great players of the present, then its outputs may reflect era biases which have been discussed throughout this work. In a very unpopular public comment, one of the authors of this work was willing to bet the under of the ZiPS 90th percentile of the Soto projections under the premise that it may have embedded era biases. This author received a lot of public flack, perhaps deservedly so, but ultimately got zero takers.

We appreciate Dan Szymborski for even taking the time to acknowledge the circus that surrounded our point. We also enjoyed Dan revealing that an unadulterated Ted Williams is indeed Juan Sotoâs closest comp.

Other adjustment strategies: Era-bridging

We revisit some of the commentary about BRLâs era-bridging method made in my previous article. Recall that BRL developed an era-bridging technique involving hierarchical Bayesian models which they claim serves the role of a statistical time machine that allows for all players to be compared directly. They state:

âThe goal is not to judge players relative to their contemporaries, but rather to compare all players directly. Hence the model that we use is a statistical time machine. We use additive models to estimate the innate ability of players, the effects of aging on performance, and the relative difficulty of each year within a sport. We measure each of these effects separated from the others. We use hierarchical models to model the distribution of players and specify separate distributions for each decade, thus allowing theâtalent pool" within each sport to change. We study the changing talent pool in each sport and address Gouldâs conjecture about the way in which populations change."

BRLâs addressing of Gouldâs conjecture is summarized with the following passage:

âThe globalization has been less pronounced in MLB, where players are drawn mainly from the United States and other countries in the Americas. Baseball has remained fairly stable within the United States, where it has been an important part of the culture for more than a century.â

This rationale is not wrong relative to the other sports under study by BRL. However, BRLâs rationale ignores segregation in its modeling construction (although segregation is mentioned by BRL), increases in the MLB eligible population relative to available roster spots, and increases in the average overall talent of that population. It also downplays the demographic change in MLB produced by racial integration as noted by Armour. In addition this model treats NL/AL players from all generations as interchangeable in the sense that they are all NL/AL caliber players regardless of which era they played. Plainly put, the expanded racial diversity of those performing in NL/AL literally meant white major leaguers who might have played a decade earlier were replaced by talented African American and Latino players that were previously excluded from MLB.

All of the above concerns are partially addressed by the modeling formulation which is parametric in nature and requires the complex changing dynamics to be captured by the parametric assumptions that they impose. In a previous article it was stated that:

âWe found that BRL did not fully account for Gouldâs conjecture in the context of baseball. We also found it odd that the BRL model predicts that a .300 hitter in 1996 will have a lower than .300 average for several seasons from 1900â20. This conflicts with the well-established notion that the talent of baseball players has improved over time. Perhaps the decadal hierarchical modeling approach did not capture the changing dynamics of the underlying talent pool or perhaps the distributional assumptions made were inappropriate.â

While it is true that the BRL approach predicts that a .300 hitter in 1996 will have a lower than .300 average for several seasons from 1900â20, it is also true that the effects of deadball era shares blame with the notion that the talent of baseball players has improved over time. That being said, the Full House Model predicts that a .300 hitter in 1996 will have a greater than .300 average for all seasons in the 1900-20 period.

But it is perhaps each modelâs handling of World War II (WWII) that best illustrates the inferiority of BRLâs era-bridging approach. According to Dan Olmsted at the The National WWII Museum over 500 major leaguers served in the military during World War II, including future Hall of Famers Ted Williams, Stan Musial, Hank Greenberg, Bob Feller, and Joe DiMaggio, not to mention the thousands of minor leaguers. There were at least 3 MLB players and 177 minor leaguers who were killed in these wars. This tally does not include far from complete tally of the wounded or the sheer number of soldiers that may have made a career out of the military or decided to pursue other professions than baseball after returning from war.

It is fair to say that WWII had gutted both the talent pool feeding into the MLB and talent level of the MLB. Our first thought would be to think that the gutted MLB would be readily apparent in a study of the changing distributions of baseball statistics. But this is not really the case. First of all, WAR is fixed to the number of possible wins and therefore exhibits no attachment to changing talent dynamics, the computation of WAR is the same regardless of the level of talent in the MLB. But certainly batting averages would be affected? No, not really. WWII drained both the batters and the pitchers and the balance between the two was preserved. Thus the dynamics articulated by Steve Jay Gould take hold. Here is a look at four statistical moments of the batting average distribution over time where the points in red correspond to seasons surrounding the peak of WWII (1941-1946):

We can see that the distribution of batting averages during WWII seasons are not really any different than those of other seasons, and they do not differ dramatically from the batting average distributions of seasons immediately preceding and following WWII. Therefore, BRLâs era-bridging hierarchical Bayesian method will not diagnose or correctly handle the WWII seasons. Their decadal and seasonal random effects will not reveal a difference in talent over those seasons. Therefore, era-bridging will overestimate the productivity of players during that time and will give false under projections for other player seasons which are mapped into the WWII baseball years.

We appreciate that Posnanski used an artistic as well as a scientific process to come up with the above rankings, and we appreciate the thinking that todayâs players are underrated compared to those who came before them. But we feel that whatever reasoning led to putting Willie Mays ahead of Babe Ruth should have also placed Rickey Henderson ahead of Ty Cobb, Albert Pujols ahead of Lou Gehrig, Cal Ripken Jr.Â ahead of Honus Wagner, and both Randy Johnson and Greg Maddux ahead of Walter Johnson.

We also note that Posnanskiâs list contains 6 players who began their career before integration in his top 10 list, and 12 players who began their career before integration in his top 25 list. By our calculations, the chance of observing 12 or more pre-integration players in a top 25 list is about 1 in 1250, and the chance of observing 6 or more pre-integration players in a top 10 list is about 1 in 230. Thus, Posnanski has included too many old time players in his rankings of the greatest all-time players. Meanwhile, the chance of observing 7 or more pre-integration players in a top 25 list is about 1 in 6, and the chance of observing 1 or more pre-integration players in a top 10 list is about 1 in 1.15. Our method is therefore right in alignment with what we would expect.

Posnanski has the advantage of not being married to a formula and can naturally account for things like steroids, amphetamine usage, and all-time talents like Trout not having enough seasons to belong to a career list based solely on career totals. We would enjoy seeing what Posnanskiâs list would look like if he started with our era-adjusted rankings. That being said, we probably need to era-adjust Negro League statistics before Posnanski weighs in. We will have those results real soon now.

Comparing a Player Outside His Era: Bill James and Tom Tango

Bill James published a fascinating conversation between Tom Tango and himself on the subject of cross-era comparisons. There are many nuggets from this conversation which deserve attention, but in the interest of brevity, we will only focus on a few segments.

Simplifying a little, Tom Tangoâs initial position is that we should only compare players to their contemporaries in the strictest of senses. He says:

âYou have about 12-15 nonpitcher in the HOF for any 10-11 year time period. If Andruw Jones [a player whose HOF candidcay that Bill and Tom are discussing] is one of the top 12 nonpitcher among his peers, great. If heâs one of the 40 nonpitchers born 1962-1992, great. (Though these numbers can be argued based on expansion.)â¦ This way, we donât have to makeâtimeline" adjustments. Thatâs me though."

Billâs response is very lengthy (although not as lengthy as what you have read here). One of his main points of response is:

"Yes, of course it is difficult to make cross-generational comparisons in baseball, but you ignore the fact that we have a constant frame of reference which applies across time and which stabilizes the data across time: Wins. IF you can state a playerâs contribution to his team in terms of wins and losses, then you have a valid basis for comparing a player from 1968 to a player in 2008âleaving only the large problem of the relative quality of play over time, and the relatively small issues of the length of the schedule and what to do with post-season play.

And, in fact, we HAVE 85% solved the problem(s) of stating a playerâs contribution to his team in terms of wins and losses. Yes, we still have the WAR/Wins and Losses Issue and the many problems inherent in WAR, but what we DO know about this issue now is much larger than what we do not knowâunlike 1975, when we had not even reached the understanding that we needed to state these contributions in constant terms, and that wins was the constant unit which guides the debate.

Tom responds with:

"Inherent in the wins-as-the-great-equalizer debate is that it treats winning percentage of .500 as a constant. This forces a specific mindset: (a) do you adjust this across time, so that a .500 win% in 1917 is not the same as in 2017? (b) do you accept it is the same, solely for the purposes of peer-comparisons?

If you accept (b), weâre holding the players accountable to their era only. And so any comparison of Ty Cobb to Rickey Henderson is limited to their comparisons to their direct peers, and then players of the early 1900s, as a group, are being treated as equals to the players of the 1980s and of today (.500 = .500). So, weâre actually comparing Cobb and Rickey through this âcommon baselineâ.

If you accept (a), you need to accept that players have gotten better across time, just like in every other sport, and so, the average player in Cobbâs time would likely be a bench player today, at best. I say this not only because players must have gotten physically stronger and faster, but also because 3/8ths of the best players today would have been precluded from playing during the segregation era. If we use players of the 1900s as any kind of benchmark, by this assumption, weâd be voting in ten players every year.

In my view, before we jump through the hoops that a careful timeline comparison would require, (including establishing which of the two assumptions to follow, of which no one will agree with anyway) letâs at least do the easy part and compare players to their direct peers."

In our view, the Full House Model IS the careful timeline comparison sought by Tom Tango, and it renders his mindset distinctions between (a) and (b) moot. The Full House Model takes statistics like WAR and corrects for its existing era-biases through a balancing of how one performs âvs their peersâ and how many people are eligible to play in the MLB.

Tom is right when he suggests that we would be voting in more players every year if we actually approach HOF candidates by their era-adjusted talent. It seems that he is stating this as a drawback which, if true, would be very disappointing considering that older playersâ statistics are inflated as a result of racial segregation.
